    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which EC2 pricing model is best for a predictable, steady-state workload that runs 24/7 and requires a 1- or 3-year commitment?", "options": ["On-Demand Instances", "Reserved Instances", "Spot Instances", "Dedicated Hosts"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Commit for savings, Partha. Reserved Instances offer up to 72% discount compared to On-Demand in exchange for a 1- or 3-year commitment — ideal for predictable, always-on workloads."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which EC2 pricing model is best for fault-tolerant, flexible workloads that can be interrupted, and can save up to 90% compared to On-Demand?", "options": ["Reserved Instances", "Dedicated Hosts", "Spot Instances", "Savings Plans"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Bid on spare capacity, Partha. Spot Instances use unused EC2 capacity at up to 90% discount, but AWS can reclaim them with a 2-minute warning — perfect for batch jobs, analytics, and fault-tolerant applications."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "A company needs EC2 instances for a new project. They are not sure about the duration or usage pattern. Which pricing model should they use?", "options": ["Reserved Instances", "Spot Instances", "On-Demand Instances", "Dedicated Hosts"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Pay as you go, Partha. On-Demand instances have no upfront commitment and no long-term contract — you pay by the hour or second. Perfect for unpredictable workloads or new projects where requirements are unknown."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which EC2 pricing model provides physical servers dedicated to a single customer, meeting regulatory requirements that prohibit multi-tenant virtualization?", "options": ["Reserved Instances", "Spot Instances", "Dedicated Instances", "Dedicated Hosts"], "correct_index": 3, "explanation": "Your own physical server, Partha. Dedicated Hosts provide an entire physical server dedicated to your use, allowing you to use existing per-socket or per-core software licenses and meet strict compliance requirements."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is the difference between Dedicated Instances and Dedicated Hosts?", "options": ["They are identical", "Dedicated Instances run on hardware dedicated to you but you cannot control host placement; Dedicated Hosts give you visibility and control over the physical server", "Dedicated Hosts are cheaper", "Dedicated Instances support BYOL; Dedicated Hosts do not"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The level of control differs, Partha. Dedicated Instances run on dedicated hardware but share it with other instances in your account. Dedicated Hosts give you a specific physical server with full visibility and control — needed for BYOL licensing."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which EC2 pricing option provides the most flexibility with no interruption risk and no commitment, but at the highest cost per hour?", "options": ["Reserved Instances", "Spot Instances", "On-Demand Instances", "Savings Plans"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Maximum flexibility, maximum cost, Partha. On-Demand instances are the most flexible — start and stop anytime with no commitments — but they are the most expensive per hour of all pricing models."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "AWS Savings Plans differ from Reserved Instances in that Savings Plans:", "options": ["Require you to specify a specific instance type and Region", "Provide savings in exchange for a commitment to a consistent amount of compute usage ($/hour) across any instance type, Region, or OS", "Only apply to EC2 and not to Lambda or Fargate", "Are only available for 3-year terms"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "More flexible commitments, Partha. Savings Plans offer flexibility to change instance type, Region, OS, and even the compute service (EC2, Lambda, Fargate) while still receiving discounts in exchange for a $/hour usage commitment."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which Amazon S3 storage class is designed for frequently accessed data and offers the highest availability and performance?", "options": ["S3 Standard-IA", "S3 Glacier", "S3 Standard", "S3 One Zone-IA"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "The default and best for frequent access, Partha. S3 Standard is designed for frequently accessed data with high durability, availability, and performance — it is the default storage class when you upload objects to S3."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which S3 storage class is designed for data accessed less than once a month, stored across multiple AZs, and costs less than S3 Standard?", "options": ["S3 Standard", "S3 Standard-IA (Infrequent Access)", "S3 One Zone-IA", "S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Infrequent but highly available, Partha. S3 Standard-IA is for data that is accessed less frequently but must be available immediately when needed — it costs less than Standard but charges a retrieval fee per GB accessed."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which S3 storage class stores data in only ONE Availability Zone, costs 20% less than Standard-IA, but has lower availability?", "options": ["S3 Standard-IA", "S3 One Zone-IA", "S3 Glacier", "S3 Intelligent-Tiering"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Single zone savings, Partha. S3 One Zone-IA stores data in a single AZ — if that AZ is destroyed, the data is lost. It is appropriate for data that can be recreated or for secondary backup copies where cost is a priority."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which S3 storage class automatically moves objects between frequent-access and infrequent-access tiers based on changing access patterns?", "options": ["S3 Standard-IA", "S3 Glacier", "S3 Intelligent-Tiering", "S3 One Zone-IA"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Let AWS optimize for you, Partha. S3 Intelligent-Tiering monitors access patterns and automatically moves objects between tiers to optimize costs — ideal when access patterns are unpredictable."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which S3 storage class is designed for long-term archive data that is rarely accessed and accepts retrieval times of minutes to hours, at the lowest storage cost?", "options": ["S3 Standard-IA", "S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval", "S3 One Zone-IA", "S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Archive at low cost, Partha. S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval (formerly S3 Glacier) is for archival data accessed once or twice a year, offering retrieval in minutes to hours at a very low storage cost."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which S3 storage class provides the LOWEST storage cost and is for data that is accessed less than once a year and can tolerate retrieval times of 12 hours or more?", "options": ["S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval", "S3 Glacier Deep Archive", "S3 One Zone-IA", "S3 Standard-IA"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The ultimate archive, Partha. S3 Glacier Deep Archive has the lowest storage cost in S3 and is designed for data that is rarely if ever accessed, with retrieval times of 12-48 hours — perfect for regulatory long-term archives."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What does Amazon S3 stand for?", "options": ["Simple Storage Solution", "Simple Storage Service", "Secure Storage System", "Scalable Storage Service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The full name, Partha. Amazon S3 stands for Amazon Simple Storage Service — an object storage service offering industry-leading scalability, availability, security, and performance."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is the maximum size of a single object that can be stored in Amazon S3?", "options": ["5 GB", "100 GB", "5 TB", "Unlimited"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Five terabytes maximum, Partha. A single S3 object can be up to 5 TB in size. Objects larger than 100 MB should use S3 Multipart Upload. There is no limit on total storage in an S3 bucket."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS database service is a fully managed relational database that supports MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle, and SQL Server?", "options": ["Amazon DynamoDB", "Amazon Redshift", "Amazon Aurora", "Amazon RDS"], "correct_index": 3, "explanation": "The managed relational database, Partha. Amazon RDS (Relational Database Service) is a fully managed relational database service supporting MySQL, PostgreSQL, MariaDB, Oracle, and SQL Server engines."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Amazon DynamoDB is best described as:", "options": ["A managed relational SQL database", "A managed NoSQL key-value and document database with single-digit millisecond performance", "A graph database for social network data", "A time-series database for IoT data"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Fast and flexible, Partha. DynamoDB is a fully managed, serverless, key-value and document NoSQL database delivering consistent single-digit millisecond performance at any scale — with no servers to manage."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS database service is designed for data warehousing and running complex analytical queries (OLAP) on petabytes of data?", "options": ["Amazon RDS", "Amazon DynamoDB", "Amazon Redshift", "Amazon Aurora"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Analyze at scale, Partha. Amazon Redshift is a fully managed, petabyte-scale data warehouse service optimized for Online Analytical Processing (OLAP) — running complex analytical queries across massive datasets."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Amazon Aurora is:", "options": ["A NoSQL database compatible with MongoDB", "A MySQL and PostgreSQL-compatible relational database that is up to 5x faster than MySQL and 3x faster than PostgreSQL", "A managed Redis cache service", "A graph database"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "AWS's own relational database, Partha. Amazon Aurora is a cloud-native relational database that combines the performance and availability of commercial databases with the simplicity and cost-effectiveness of open-source databases."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service provides a managed in-memory cache to speed up database queries by storing frequently accessed data in memory?", "options": ["Amazon RDS", "Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX)", "Amazon ElastiCache", "Amazon MemoryDB"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Speed up with cache, Partha. Amazon ElastiCache provides managed Redis or Memcached caches that store frequently accessed data in memory, dramatically reducing database load and improving application response times."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is AWS Lambda?", "options": ["A managed container orchestration service", "A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events without requiring server management", "A virtual machine hosting service", "A managed batch processing service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Serverless simplicity, Partha. AWS Lambda runs your code in response to events (HTTP requests, S3 uploads, DynamoDB changes, etc.) without you needing to provision, manage, or scale any servers."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is the maximum execution timeout for a single AWS Lambda function invocation?", "options": ["30 seconds", "5 minutes", "15 minutes", "1 hour"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Know the limits, Partha. AWS Lambda functions have a maximum execution timeout of 15 minutes (900 seconds). For longer-running processes, use EC2, ECS, or Step Functions instead."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "An Elastic Load Balancer (ELB) that operates at Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS) and supports advanced routing rules like host-based and path-based routing is called:", "options": ["Classic Load Balancer", "Network Load Balancer", "Application Load Balancer", "Gateway Load Balancer"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Layer 7 intelligence, Partha. The Application Load Balancer (ALB) operates at Layer 7 and understands HTTP/HTTPS, enabling advanced routing rules based on URL path, hostname, headers, and query strings."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which type of Elastic Load Balancer operates at Layer 4 (TCP/UDP) and is capable of handling millions of requests per second with ultra-low latency?", "options": ["Application Load Balancer", "Network Load Balancer", "Classic Load Balancer", "Gateway Load Balancer"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Layer 4 speed, Partha. The Network Load Balancer (NLB) operates at Layer 4 (TCP/UDP), handling extreme traffic volumes with very low latency — ideal for applications requiring high performance and static IP addresses."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is AWS Auto Scaling?", "options": ["Automatically upgrading EC2 instance types to larger sizes", "Automatically adjusting the number of EC2 instances (or other resources) based on demand", "Automatically applying OS patches to EC2 instances", "Automatically moving data between S3 storage classes"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Scale automatically, Partha. Auto Scaling monitors your applications and automatically adjusts capacity — adding instances when demand rises and removing them when demand drops — maintaining performance and minimizing costs."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Amazon CloudFront is best described as:", "options": ["A managed relational database", "A global Content Delivery Network (CDN) that delivers content to users with low latency", "A virtual private network service", "A DNS routing service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Speed the content delivery, Partha. Amazon CloudFront is a CDN that caches content (web pages, images, videos) at Edge Locations globally, delivering it to users from the nearest location for low latency."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Amazon Route 53 is primarily used for:", "options": ["Routing EC2 instances to the internet", "Domain Name System (DNS) management and domain registration", "Content delivery and caching", "Load balancing between AWS Regions"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The DNS service, Partha. Amazon Route 53 is a scalable and highly available Domain Name System (DNS) web service used to register domains, route users to applications, and perform health checks."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which Route 53 routing policy routes traffic to resources based on geographic location of the user?", "options": ["Simple routing", "Weighted routing", "Failover routing", "Geolocation routing"], "correct_index": 3, "explanation": "Route by location, Partha. Geolocation routing directs users to specific resources based on their geographic location — for example, routing European users to EU-based servers and US users to US-based servers."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service is used to transfer large amounts of data (petabytes) to AWS when internet bandwidth is insufficient or too costly?", "options": ["AWS Direct Connect", "AWS Snowball", "Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration", "AWS DataSync"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Ship the data physically, Partha. AWS Snowball is a physical data transfer device — you load your data onto it and ship it to AWS. It can transfer up to 80 TB per device, making it ideal for large migrations."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service would you use for migrating exabytes of data to AWS using a fleet of shipping containers?", "options": ["AWS Snowball", "AWS Snowmobile", "AWS Storage Gateway", "AWS DataSync"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The biggest migration, Partha. AWS Snowmobile is an exabyte-scale data transfer service — a 45-foot long ruggedized shipping container pulled by a semi-trailer truck, capable of transferring up to 100 PB per truck."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is Amazon VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)?", "options": ["A service for managing virtual private servers", "A logically isolated section of the AWS Cloud where you can launch AWS resources in a defined virtual network", "A VPN service connecting on-premises to AWS", "A managed container service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Your private network in AWS, Partha. Amazon VPC lets you provision a logically isolated virtual network where you have complete control over network configuration — IP ranges, subnets, routing tables, and internet gateways."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is the purpose of an Internet Gateway in a VPC?", "options": ["To connect two VPCs together", "To allow resources in a VPC to communicate with the internet", "To connect the VPC to an on-premises network", "To provide DNS resolution within the VPC"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The door to the internet, Partha. An Internet Gateway is a VPC component that enables communication between resources in your VPC and the public internet — required for any resource in a public subnet to be internet-accessible."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service allows you to run Docker containers without managing the underlying server infrastructure?", "options": ["Amazon EC2", "Amazon EKS", "AWS Fargate", "Amazon ECS on EC2"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Serverless containers, Partha. AWS Fargate is a serverless compute engine for containers that removes the need to provision and manage EC2 instances — you define the container, Fargate handles the infrastructure."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is Amazon ECS?", "options": ["Elastic Cache Service", "Elastic Container Service — a fully managed container orchestration service", "Elastic Compute Service", "Edge Content Service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Orchestrate containers, Partha. Amazon ECS (Elastic Container Service) is a fully managed container orchestration service that allows you to run, stop, and manage Docker containers on a cluster of EC2 instances or Fargate."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service is a fully managed Kubernetes service?", "options": ["Amazon ECS", "AWS Fargate", "Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service)", "AWS Batch"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Managed Kubernetes, Partha. Amazon EKS is a fully managed Kubernetes service that handles the control plane for you — so you can run Kubernetes workloads without managing the underlying Kubernetes infrastructure."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Amazon SNS (Simple Notification Service) is best used for:", "options": ["Queuing messages between microservices", "Sending messages to multiple subscribers simultaneously (pub/sub) via email, SMS, HTTP, or Lambda", "Scheduling batch jobs", "Storing message streams for analytics"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Publish and notify, Partha. Amazon SNS is a pub/sub messaging service — a publisher sends one message to a topic, and SNS fans it out to all subscribers (email, SMS, SQS queues, Lambda functions, etc.) simultaneously."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Amazon SQS (Simple Queue Service) is best used for:", "options": ["Sending push notifications to mobile devices", "Decoupling application components by storing messages in a queue for reliable point-to-point delivery", "Real-time streaming of large data volumes", "Broadcasting messages to multiple subscribers"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Decouple the components, Partha. Amazon SQS is a message queue service that stores messages until they are processed, allowing producers and consumers to work independently — preventing one slow component from blocking another."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service would you use to monitor the performance of EC2 instances and set alarms when CPU usage exceeds 80%?", "options": ["AWS CloudTrail", "Amazon CloudWatch", "AWS Config", "AWS X-Ray"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Monitor and alert, Partha. Amazon CloudWatch collects metrics, logs, and events from AWS resources. You can create alarms that trigger actions (like SNS notifications or Auto Scaling) when metrics cross defined thresholds."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is AWS CloudFormation?", "options": ["A service for monitoring cloud resource performance", "An Infrastructure as Code (IaC) service that allows you to provision and manage AWS resources using templates", "A security scanning service for cloud configurations", "A cost forecasting and budgeting service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Code your infrastructure, Partha. CloudFormation is AWS's IaC service — you write templates (in JSON or YAML) that describe your desired infrastructure, and CloudFormation provisions and manages it consistently and repeatably."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service provides a managed workflow orchestration service for coordinating multiple AWS services and Lambda functions?", "options": ["Amazon SQS", "Amazon SNS", "AWS Step Functions", "Amazon EventBridge"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Coordinate the steps, Partha. AWS Step Functions is a serverless orchestration service that lets you sequence AWS Lambda functions and other services into workflows, with built-in error handling and state management."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS compute service is best suited for running a long-running machine learning training job that requires GPU acceleration?", "options": ["AWS Lambda", "AWS Fargate", "Amazon EC2 with GPU-optimized instances (P-class or G-class)", "AWS Batch"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "GPU power on demand, Partha. For GPU-intensive workloads like ML training, EC2 GPU-optimized instances (p3, p4, g4) are the right choice. Lambda and Fargate have no GPU support, and Batch uses EC2 under the hood."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration?", "options": ["A feature that compresses files before uploading to S3", "A feature that uses CloudFront Edge Locations to accelerate long-distance S3 uploads", "A feature that automatically replicates S3 data to multiple Regions", "A feature that converts S3 objects to a more efficient format"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Accelerate global uploads, Partha. S3 Transfer Acceleration routes uploads through Amazon CloudFront's globally distributed Edge Locations, using AWS's optimized network to speed up transfers from distant locations."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service provides fully managed, petabyte-scale data lake storage and analytics built on S3?", "options": ["Amazon Redshift", "AWS Glue", "Amazon Athena", "AWS Lake Formation"], "correct_index": 3, "explanation": "Build the data lake, Partha. AWS Lake Formation simplifies building, securing, and managing data lakes on Amazon S3 — handling data ingestion, cataloging, permissions, and access controls in a centralized way."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service allows you to query data directly in S3 using standard SQL without setting up a database?", "options": ["Amazon Redshift", "Amazon RDS", "Amazon Athena", "AWS Glue"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Query S3 with SQL, Partha. Amazon Athena is a serverless interactive query service that lets you analyze data stored in S3 using standard SQL — with no infrastructure to manage and you only pay for the queries you run."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS)?", "options": ["Object storage for files and backups", "A block-level storage volume that attaches to EC2 instances like a hard drive", "A network-attached file system for multiple EC2 instances", "A managed database storage service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The EC2 hard drive, Partha. Amazon EBS provides persistent block storage volumes that attach to EC2 instances — like a virtual hard drive that persists independently of the EC2 instance's lifecycle."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "What is Amazon EFS (Elastic File System)?", "options": ["A block storage service that attaches to EC2 instances", "A managed NFS file system that can be mounted by multiple EC2 instances simultaneously", "An object storage service similar to S3", "A database file management service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Shared file storage, Partha. Amazon EFS is a fully managed NFS file system that can be mounted concurrently by thousands of EC2 instances across multiple AZs — unlike EBS, which attaches to only one instance at a time."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service allows you to run a fully managed Apache Kafka-compatible message streaming service?", "options": ["Amazon SQS", "Amazon SNS", "Amazon Kinesis", "Amazon MSK (Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka)"], "correct_index": 3, "explanation": "Managed Kafka, Partha. Amazon MSK is a fully managed service for Apache Kafka, handling provisioning, configuration, and maintenance of Kafka clusters for real-time streaming data pipelines and applications."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Amazon Kinesis Data Streams is used for:", "options": ["Batch processing of large datasets stored in S3", "Real-time processing of streaming data like logs, clickstreams, and IoT sensor data", "Queuing messages between application components", "Distributing content globally via CDN"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Stream in real time, Partha. Amazon Kinesis Data Streams collects and processes large streams of data records in real time — essential for real-time analytics, monitoring, and event-driven architectures."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "AWS Elastic Beanstalk is best described as:", "options": ["A container orchestration service", "A Platform as a Service (PaaS) that handles deployment, scaling, and monitoring of web applications automatically", "An Infrastructure as Code tool", "A managed Kubernetes service"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Deploy without the complexity, Partha. Elastic Beanstalk is a PaaS service — you upload your code, and it automatically handles capacity provisioning, load balancing, auto scaling, and health monitoring."},
    {"domain": "Domain 3: Cloud Technology and Services", "question": "Which AWS service provides a fully managed, distributed in-memory caching service compatible with Redis?", "options": ["Amazon RDS", "Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator", "Amazon ElastiCache for Redis", "Amazon MemoryDB for Redis"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Cache with Redis, Partha. Amazon ElastiCache for Redis provides a fully managed, in-memory Redis cache. Redis supports advanced data structures (lists, sets, hashes) making it useful for caching, sessions, and leaderboards."},

