    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which type of AWS Free Tier offer provides services free for 12 months from the date you create your AWS account?", "options": ["Always Free", "12-Month Free Tier", "Free Trials", "Pay As You Go"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "A year to explore, Partha. The 12-Month Free Tier provides free access to services like EC2 (750 hours/month of t2.micro), S3 (5 GB), and RDS (750 hours/month) for the first 12 months after account creation."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which type of AWS Free Tier never expires and is available to all AWS customers regardless of account age?", "options": ["12-Month Free Tier", "Free Trials", "Always Free", "Developer Tier"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Forever free, Partha. Always Free offers do not expire — they are available to all AWS customers indefinitely. Examples include AWS Lambda (1 million free requests/month) and DynamoDB (25 GB storage)."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "A company wants to try Amazon SageMaker for 2 months before committing. Which Free Tier type applies?", "options": ["Always Free", "12-Month Free Tier", "Free Trials", "Spot Pricing"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Try before you buy, Partha. Free Trials are service-specific short-term offers that begin from the date you first activate a service — like the 2-month free trial of SageMaker. They expire regardless of account age."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Under the AWS Free Tier, how many hours per month of Amazon EC2 t2.micro or t3.micro usage are included for the first 12 months?", "options": ["100 hours", "500 hours", "750 hours", "1000 hours"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Know the free tier limits, Partha. The AWS Free Tier includes 750 hours per month of EC2 t2.micro or t3.micro instance usage for 12 months — enough to run one instance continuously for the entire month."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS tool helps you estimate the cost of your AWS architecture before deploying it?", "options": ["AWS Cost Explorer", "AWS Budgets", "AWS Pricing Calculator", "AWS Billing Dashboard"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Plan the costs first, Partha. The AWS Pricing Calculator (calculator.aws) lets you model your expected AWS architecture and estimate the monthly and annual costs before you deploy anything."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS tool lets you visualize, understand, and analyze your AWS costs and usage over time?", "options": ["AWS Pricing Calculator", "AWS Budgets", "AWS Cost Explorer", "AWS Trusted Advisor"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Understand your spending, Partha. AWS Cost Explorer provides an interactive graphical interface to visualize cost and usage patterns over time, identify trends, and pinpoint areas to optimize spending."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS service lets you set custom alerts to notify you when your costs or usage exceed a threshold you define?", "options": ["AWS Cost Explorer", "AWS Pricing Calculator", "AWS Budgets", "AWS Cost and Usage Report"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Set spending limits, Partha. AWS Budgets lets you set custom cost and usage budgets and receive alerts via email or SNS when your actual or forecasted costs exceed your defined thresholds."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS service provides the most granular, detailed data about your AWS costs and usage and can be exported to S3 for analysis?", "options": ["AWS Cost Explorer", "AWS Budgets", "AWS Pricing Calculator", "AWS Cost and Usage Report (CUR)"], "correct_index": 3, "explanation": "The most detailed billing data, Partha. The AWS Cost and Usage Report (CUR) contains the most comprehensive set of cost and usage data available, with line-item detail that can be analyzed with Athena or QuickSight."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What is AWS Consolidated Billing?", "options": ["A single monthly invoice for all resources in one account", "A feature of AWS Organizations that combines billing for multiple accounts into one monthly invoice, with potential volume discounts", "A service that consolidates cost and usage reports", "A feature that automatically pays Reserved Instance bills"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "One bill for all, Partha. AWS Organizations' Consolidated Billing combines usage from all member accounts, potentially qualifying for volume pricing discounts, and generates a single monthly invoice for the entire organization."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "A company has 10 AWS accounts in an AWS Organization. Some accounts use Reserved Instances. How does Consolidated Billing treat unused Reserved Instance hours?", "options": ["They are lost and cannot be shared", "They can be shared across accounts in the organization to reduce costs", "They convert to On-Demand at the reserved price", "They roll over to the next month"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Share the savings, Partha. With Consolidated Billing, unused Reserved Instance hours from one account can be applied to matching On-Demand usage in other accounts within the organization, maximizing the value of reserved capacity."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What are the three AWS Support plans above the Basic plan?", "options": ["Free, Starter, Enterprise", "Developer, Business, Enterprise", "Starter, Professional, Enterprise", "Basic, Advanced, Premium"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Know the tiers, Partha. The four AWS Support plans are: Basic (free), Developer, Business, and Enterprise. Each tier provides progressively more support features, faster response times, and additional services."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "The AWS Basic Support plan includes:", "options": ["24/7 phone and chat access to Cloud Support Engineers", "Access to Trusted Advisor full checks and health dashboard only", "Access to AWS documentation, whitepapers, and support forums — but no technical support from AWS engineers", "1-hour response time for critical issues"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Documentation only, Partha. AWS Basic Support (free) includes access to documentation, whitepapers, support forums, and service health dashboard — but NO technical support cases with AWS engineers. You must upgrade for that."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "The AWS Developer Support plan is best for:", "options": ["Production workloads requiring fast response times", "Experimenting with AWS and needing email-only technical support during business hours", "24/7 phone support and access to a Technical Account Manager", "Enterprise applications with mission-critical requirements"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Development and experimentation, Partha. Developer Support provides email access to Cloud Support Associates during business hours, with response time of < 24 hours for general guidance and < 12 hours for system impaired cases."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS Support plan provides 24/7 phone, email, and chat access to Cloud Support Engineers, and is recommended for production workloads?", "options": ["Basic", "Developer", "Business", "Enterprise"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Production-ready support, Partha. AWS Business Support provides 24/7 phone, email, and chat access to Cloud Support Engineers, full Trusted Advisor checks, and a 1-hour response time for production system down issues."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS Support plan includes a dedicated Technical Account Manager (TAM) and access to a Concierge Support Team?", "options": ["Developer", "Business", "Enterprise", "Enterprise On-Ramp"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "The highest tier, Partha. AWS Enterprise Support includes a dedicated Technical Account Manager (TAM) who provides proactive guidance, and access to the Concierge Support Team for billing and account assistance."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What is the response time for a 'Business-Critical System Down' case under the AWS Enterprise Support plan?", "options": ["24 hours", "4 hours", "1 hour", "15 minutes"], "correct_index": 3, "explanation": "Fastest response for critical issues, Partha. AWS Enterprise Support guarantees a response time of less than 15 minutes for business-critical system down cases — the fastest response time available across all support tiers."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What is the response time for a 'Production System Down' case under the AWS Business Support plan?", "options": ["15 minutes", "1 hour", "4 hours", "12 hours"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Critical production support, Partha. AWS Business Support guarantees a less-than-1-hour response time for production system down cases — critical for businesses that cannot afford extended downtime."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS Support plan is the MINIMUM required to get 24/7 access to Cloud Support Engineers via phone?", "options": ["Basic", "Developer", "Business", "Enterprise"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Business unlocks phone support, Partha. Only Business and Enterprise plans include 24/7 phone access to Cloud Support Engineers. Developer only offers email during business hours, and Basic has no engineer access at all."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS tool was designed to help customers calculate the total cost of ownership (TCO) when comparing on-premises infrastructure to AWS?", "options": ["AWS Pricing Calculator", "AWS Cost Explorer", "AWS Migration Evaluator (formerly TCO Calculator)", "AWS Budgets"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Compare the true cost, Partha. AWS Migration Evaluator (formerly the TCO Calculator) helps organizations compare the total cost of ownership of on-premises infrastructure versus equivalent AWS deployments, including hidden costs."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What is the AWS Marketplace?", "options": ["A store for buying physical AWS hardware", "An online catalog where customers can find, buy, and deploy third-party software that runs on AWS", "A marketplace for AWS engineers to find consulting work", "A store for purchasing AWS Reserved Instances from other customers"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Third-party software on AWS, Partha. AWS Marketplace is a digital catalog with thousands of software listings from independent software vendors (ISVs) — you can find, buy, and deploy software directly to your AWS environment."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Three AWS Reserved Instance payment options are:", "options": ["On-Demand, Spot, and Reserved", "All Upfront, Partial Upfront, and No Upfront", "1-Year, 2-Year, and 3-Year", "Standard, Convertible, and Scheduled"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Three ways to pay, Partha. Reserved Instances have three payment options: All Upfront (highest discount), Partial Upfront (medium discount), and No Upfront (lowest discount). Longer terms and more upfront payment = greater savings."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What is the difference between a Standard Reserved Instance and a Convertible Reserved Instance?", "options": ["Standard RIs offer deeper discounts but cannot be exchanged; Convertible RIs can be exchanged for different instance attributes but offer lower discounts", "Standard RIs can be resold; Convertible RIs cannot", "Convertible RIs are cheaper than Standard RIs", "They are identical products with different names"], "correct_index": 0, "explanation": "Flexibility versus savings, Partha. Standard RIs offer the highest discounts but lock you into specific instance attributes. Convertible RIs offer lower discounts but can be exchanged for RIs of equal or greater value, providing more flexibility."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "A company purchases Reserved Instances but their workload requirements change and they no longer need them. What can they do with Standard Reserved Instances?", "options": ["Return them to AWS for a full refund", "Sell them in the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace", "Convert them to On-Demand instances automatically", "They cannot be transferred or sold"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The secondary market, Partha. Standard Reserved Instances can be sold in the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace if you no longer need them — allowing you to recoup some of the cost by selling to other customers."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What does the AWS Free Tier offer for Amazon S3 during the first 12 months?", "options": ["Unlimited storage", "5 GB of standard storage, 20,000 GET requests, and 2,000 PUT requests per month", "100 GB of standard storage", "5 TB of Glacier storage"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The S3 free tier, Partha. The 12-month free tier for S3 includes 5 GB of standard storage, 20,000 GET requests, and 2,000 PUT requests per month — enough for small applications and experimentation."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "AWS pricing for most services follows which model?", "options": ["Fixed monthly subscription regardless of usage", "Pay-as-you-go with no upfront costs and no termination fees", "Annual subscription with usage caps", "Tiered pricing based on company size"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Pay only for what you use, Partha. AWS follows a pay-as-you-go model — you pay only for the services you consume, with no upfront costs and no minimum fees. Stop using a service and you stop paying immediately."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which factor affects the pricing of Amazon EC2?", "options": ["The age of your AWS account", "Instance type, Region, OS, and whether On-Demand, Reserved, or Spot pricing is used", "The number of IAM users in your account", "The support plan you have selected"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Multiple factors determine cost, Partha. EC2 pricing depends on instance type (size and family), the AWS Region (us-east-1 is typically cheapest), operating system (Windows costs more than Linux), and the pricing model chosen."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS billing feature provides a detailed breakdown of costs by service, region, and tags for a large enterprise?", "options": ["AWS Budgets", "AWS Cost Explorer", "Cost Allocation Tags with Cost and Usage Reports", "AWS Consolidated Billing"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Tag for cost accountability, Partha. Cost Allocation Tags let you assign metadata (like project name or department) to resources. Combined with the Cost and Usage Report, you can break down costs by any dimension you define."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What is the purpose of AWS Budgets Actions?", "options": ["Automatically shutting down AWS accounts that exceed budgets", "Automatically applying IAM policies, Service Control Policies, or EC2/RDS actions when a budget threshold is breached", "Sending SMS alerts when costs are exceeded", "Requesting a billing credit from AWS"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "Take automatic action, Partha. AWS Budgets Actions allows you to automatically enforce actions — like applying an IAM policy to restrict access or stopping EC2 instances — when a budget threshold is crossed, preventing further overspending."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Which AWS service provides real-time guidance to help you provision resources following AWS best practices for cost optimization, performance, and security?", "options": ["AWS Config", "AWS CloudTrail", "AWS Trusted Advisor", "AWS Cost Explorer"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Your cloud advisor, Partha. AWS Trusted Advisor analyzes your account and provides recommendations across five categories: Cost Optimization (e.g., idle EC2), Performance, Security, Fault Tolerance, and Service Limits."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "How many core Trusted Advisor checks are available to ALL AWS customers regardless of support plan?", "options": ["0 — all checks require Business or Enterprise support", "7 core security and service limit checks", "Full access to all checks", "Only cost optimization checks"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "7 checks for everyone, Partha. All AWS customers get 7 core Trusted Advisor checks covering basic security and service limits (like open S3 buckets and MFA on root). Full Trusted Advisor access requires Business or Enterprise support."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "What is the AWS Enterprise On-Ramp Support plan?", "options": ["A support plan for startups", "A tier between Business and Enterprise providing a pool of TAMs and 30-minute response for critical cases", "An AWS Partner program", "A free trial of Enterprise support"], "correct_index": 1, "explanation": "The bridge tier, Partha. Enterprise On-Ramp sits between Business and full Enterprise support — it includes access to a pool of Technical Account Managers and < 30-minute response for critical cases, at a lower cost than full Enterprise."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "A startup wants to launch a new product and needs to estimate AWS costs for different architectural options. Which tool should they use?", "options": ["AWS Cost Explorer", "AWS Budgets", "AWS Pricing Calculator", "AWS TCO Calculator"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Plan before you build, Partha. The AWS Pricing Calculator is the right tool for estimating and comparing costs for different architectural options before any resources are deployed — it is free to use and requires no AWS account."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Data transfer IN to AWS from the internet is priced at:", "options": ["$0.09 per GB", "$0.05 per GB", "$0 (free)", "$0.01 per GB"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Inbound is free, Partha. Data transfer INTO AWS from the internet is free. AWS charges for data transferred OUT of AWS to the internet — the 'egress' direction. This encourages moving data into AWS and keeping it there."},
    {"domain": "Domain 4: Billing, Pricing, and Support", "question": "Data transfer between AWS services in the SAME Availability Zone is priced at:", "options": ["Standard data transfer rates", "$0.01 per GB", "$0 (free)", "Regional transfer rates"], "correct_index": 2, "explanation": "Same AZ transfer is free, Partha. Data transferred between AWS services within the same Availability Zone is free. Transfer between AZs in the same Region incurs a small charge, and transfer between Regions costs more."},
